<paragraph blockId="9.[178,1085,1514,1595]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1222">
<taxonomicName authority="(SICHEL, 1868)" baseAuthorityName="SICHEL" baseAuthorityYear="1868" box="[178,844,1514,1536]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Amegilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="1222" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="quadrifasciata" subGenus="Amegilla" subSpecies="maderae">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[178,762,1514,1536]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1222">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[178,272,1514,1536]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="1222">Amegilla</emphasis>
(
<emphasis bold="true" box="[293,387,1514,1536]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="1222">Amegilla</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[409,663,1514,1536]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="1222">quadrifasciata maderae</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="SICHEL F" box="[684,762,1514,1536]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1222" refId="ref10106" refString="SICHEL F. J. (1868): Hymenoptera mellifera. - In: Die Reise der osterr eichischen Fregatte Novara um die Erde in den Jahren 1857, 1858, 1859 unter den Befehlen des Commodore B. von Wullerstorf-Urbair. Zoologischer Theil, 2. Band, l. Abtheilung, A., Hymenoptera (bearb. v. H. de Salissure). Wien (k. - k. Hof- u. Staatsdruckerei): 143 - 156." type="journal volume" year="1868">SICHEL</bibRefCitation>
</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[782,844,1514,1536]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1222">1868)</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[845,850,1514,1536]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1222">:</emphasis>
Based on males and females, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sichel" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[270,388,1544,1565]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Amegilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="1222" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maderae">
<emphasis box="[270,388,1544,1565]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="1222">A. maderae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been validly described by 
<bibRefCitation author="SICHEL F" box="[709,860,1544,1566]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1222" refId="ref10106" refString="SICHEL F. J. (1868): Hymenoptera mellifera. - In: Die Reise der osterr eichischen Fregatte Novara um die Erde in den Jahren 1857, 1858, 1859 unter den Befehlen des Commodore B. von Wullerstorf-Urbair. Zoologischer Theil, 2. Band, l. Abtheilung, A., Hymenoptera (bearb. v. H. de Salissure). Wien (k. - k. Hof- u. Staatsdruckerei): 143 - 156." type="journal volume" year="1868">SICHEL (1868)</bibRefCitation>
. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="DOURS J" pageId="9" pageNumber="1222" refId="ref8330" refString="DOURS J. A. (1869): Monographie iconographicque du genre Anthophora Latr. - Mem. Soc. Linn. Nord de la France, Amiens. 211 pp." type="book" year="1869">DOURS (1869)</bibRefCitation>
, the specimens from 
<collectingRegion box="[474,558,1573,1595]" country="Portugal" name="Madeira" pageId="9" pageNumber="1222">Madeira</collectingRegion>
are only a variety (
<emphasis box="[770,858,1573,1594]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="1222">maderae</emphasis>
) of 
<taxonomicName authority="(DE VILLERS, 1798)" baseAuthorityName="DE VILLERS" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[906,1085,1573,1595]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Amegilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadrifasciata">
<emphasis box="[906,1085,1573,1595]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="1222">A. quadrifasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[178,1085,219,270]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">
(DE VILLERS, 1798). 
<bibRefCitation author="ALFKEN J" box="[398,557,219,241]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" pagination="1 - 2" refId="ref7742" refString="ALFKEN J. D. (1940): Die Arthropodenfauna von Madeira nach den Ergebnissen der Reise von Prof. Dr. O. Lundblad Juli - August 1935. XXV. Hymenoptera: Prosopis, Andrena, Anthophora, Megachile und Osmia. - Arkiv for zoologi (Uppsala) 32 (4): 1 - 2." type="journal article" year="1940">ALFKEN (1940)</bibRefCitation>
accepted the species status, but 
<bibRefCitation author="LIEFTINCK M" box="[903,1081,219,241]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" pagination="1 - 41" refId="ref9469" refString="LIEFTINCK M. A. (1956): Revision of some oriental Anthophorine bees of the genus Amegilla Friese (Hymenoptera, Apoidea). - Zoolog. Verhandelingen 30: 1 - 41." type="journal article" year="1956">LIEFTINCK (1956</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="LIEFTINCK M" box="[178,230,248,270]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" pagination="1 - 34" refId="ref9505" refString="LIEFTINCK M. A. (1958): Entomological results of the Finnish expedition to the Canary Islands 1947 - 1951. No. 16. A preliminary account of the bees of the Canary Islands (Hym., Apoidea). - Commentati ones Biologicae Societas Scientiarum Fennica 18: 1 - 34." type="journal article" year="1958">1958</bibRefCitation>
) referred to the species as 
<taxonomicName authority="(DE VILLERS, 1798)" baseAuthorityName="DE VILLERS" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[500,883,248,270]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Amegilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadrifasciata">
<emphasis box="[500,676,248,269]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">A. quadrifasciata</emphasis>
(DE VILLERS, 1798)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[178,1085,285,571]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">
There are certain morphological differences: In 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="DE VILLERS" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[679,857,285,307]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Amegilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadrifasciata">
<emphasis box="[679,857,285,307]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">A. quadrifasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the tergite bands are wider than the tergite terminal part. Tergite 1 has light hairs in the centre. In 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sichel" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[967,1084,315,336]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Amegilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maderae">
<emphasis box="[967,1084,315,336]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">A. maderae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the tergite bands are narrow, and tergite 1 has dark to black hairs in the centre (checked by A.W. Ebmer). H.-R. Schwenninger (Natural Museum of Stuttgart) analysed the genitalia of specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[436,505,403,424]" name="France" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">France</collectingCountry>
(Agay, Saint Raphaël, Côte d’Azur), Lanzarote (Playa Blanca), and Madeira (Cabo Girão, Câmara de Lobos). Certain differences can be detected; however, there is morphological variation, so no clear separating characteristics could be found. Because of the lack of differences in the genital structures, the actual status is 
<emphasis box="[290,587,520,541]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="DE VILLERS" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[290,479,520,541]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Amegilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadrifasciata">A. quadrifasciata</taxonomicName>
maderae
</emphasis>
. Further morphological, morphometric, and molecular investigations will be necessary.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="10.[178,1085,585,902]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">
<taxonomicName authority="KRUGER, 1956" authorityName="KRUGER" authorityYear="1956" box="[178,836,585,608]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="terrestris" subGenus="Bombus" subSpecies="lusitanicus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[178,753,585,608]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[178,264,586,608]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">Bombus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis bold="true" box="[294,380,586,608]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">Bombus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[410,639,586,608]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">terrestris lusitanicus</emphasis>
KRÜGER
</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[782,836,587,608]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">1956</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[836,841,587,608]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">:</emphasis>
The 
<taxonomicName box="[924,1005,587,608]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[924,1005,587,608]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">Bombus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taxon ‘ 
<emphasis box="[186,310,616,637]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">maderensis’</emphasis>
has been regarded as a species of its own by some authors (
<bibRefCitation author="ERLANDSSON S" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" pagination="187 - 192" refId="ref8478" refString="ERLANDSSON S. (1979): Bombus canariensis Per. and Bombus maderensis n. sp. from the Macaronesian islands. - Cent. Scand. 10: 187 - 192." type="journal article" year="1979">ERLANDSSON, 1979</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="RASMONT P" box="[241,410,646,668]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" pagination="135 - 160" refId="ref9871" refString="RASMONT P. (1984): Les bourdons du genre Bombus Latreille sensu stricto en Europe occidentale et centrale (Hymenoptera, Apidae). - Spixiana 7: 135 - 160." type="journal article" year="1984">RASMONT, 1984</bibRefCitation>
). This was not accepted by 
<bibRefCitation author="RASMONT P &amp; COPPEE A &amp; MICHEZ D" box="[695,928,645,668]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" pagination="243 - 250" refId="ref9905" refString="RASMONT P., COPPEE A., MICHEZ D. &amp; T. D. MEULEMEESTER (2008): An overview of the Bombus terrestris (L. 1758) subspecies (Hymenoptera: Apidae). - Annales de la Soc iete entomologique de France 44, 243 - 250." type="journal article" year="2008">RASMONT et al. (2008)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="WILLIAMS P &amp; BROWN M &amp; CAROLAN J &amp; AN J &amp; GOULSON D &amp; AYTEKIN A &amp; BEST L &amp; BYVALTSEV A &amp; CEDERBERG B &amp; DAWSON R &amp; HUANG J &amp; ITO M &amp; MONFARED A &amp; RAINA R &amp; HEMPEL P &amp; SHEELD C &amp; SIMA P" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref10719" refString="WILLIAMS P. H., BROWN M. J. F., CAROLAN J. C., AN J., GOULSON D., AYTEKIN A. M., BEST L. R., BYVALTSEV A. M., CEDERBERG B., DAWSON R., HUANG J., ITO M., MONFARED A., RAINA R. H., SCHMID- HEMPEL P., SHEELD C. S., SIMA P. &amp; Z. XIE (2012): Unveiling cryptic species of the bumblebee subgenus Bombus s. str. worldwide with COI barcodes (Hymenoptera: Apidae). - Systematics and Biodiversity iFirst: 1 - 36." type="book chapter" year="2012">WILLIAMS et al. (2012)</bibRefCitation>
. We will follow 
<bibRefCitation author="RASMONT P &amp; COPPEE A &amp; MICHEZ D" box="[480,716,675,697]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" pagination="243 - 250" refId="ref9905" refString="RASMONT P., COPPEE A., MICHEZ D. &amp; T. D. MEULEMEESTER (2008): An overview of the Bombus terrestris (L. 1758) subspecies (Hymenoptera: Apidae). - Annales de la Soc iete entomologique de France 44, 243 - 250." type="journal article" year="2008">RASMONT et al. (2008)</bibRefCitation>
, who assigned the specimens of the 
<collectingRegion box="[178,262,704,726]" country="Portugal" name="Madeira" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">Madeira</collectingRegion>
Archipelago to 
<emphasis box="[433,675,704,726]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[433,557,705,726]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="terrestris">B. terrestris</taxonomicName>
lusitanicus
</emphasis>
; see also 
<bibRefCitation author="COPPEE A" box="[781,937,703,726]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" refId="ref8150" refString="COPPEE A. (2012): Bombus terrestris (L. 1758): A complex species or a species complex? - Intraspecific pheromonal and genetic variations of Bombus terrestris (L.). Impacts on the speciation. - PhD thesis. Unive rsite de Mons, Laboratoire de Zoologie." type="book" year="2012">COPPÉE (2012)</bibRefCitation>
. The morphological characteristics of the former 
<taxonomicName authority="PEREZ, 1895" authorityName="PEREZ" authorityYear="1895" box="[554,841,732,755]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canariensis">
<emphasis box="[554,701,734,755]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">B. canariensis</emphasis>
PÉREZ, 1895
</taxonomicName>
, are not strongly divergent from the broad variation of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[518,640,763,784]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" sensu="lato" species="terrestris">
<emphasis box="[518,640,763,784]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">B. terrestris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[649,678,763,785]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" sensu="lato">s.l.</taxonomicNameLabel>
However, a molecular genetic analysis by 
<bibRefCitation author="WIDMER A &amp; HEMPEL P &amp; ESTOUP A" box="[214,444,792,814]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" pagination="563 - 572" refId="ref10667" refString="WIDMER A., SCHMID- HEMPEL P., ESTOUP A. &amp; A. SCHOLL (1998): Population genetic structure and colonization history of Bombus terrestris s. l. (Hymenoptera: Apidae) from the Canary Islands and Madeira. - Heredity 81: 563 - 572" type="journal article" year="1998">WIDMER et al. (1998)</bibRefCitation>
supported the distinctness of the Canary Island populations from the European mainland populations of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[635,757,822,843]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="terrestris">
<emphasis box="[635,757,822,843]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">B. terrestris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This indicates that they have a longer genetic separation on the archipelago and underlines that the populations are native.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[178,1085,917,1115]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">
Specimens from 
<collectingRegion box="[367,451,917,939]" country="Portugal" name="Madeira" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">Madeira</collectingRegion>
show genetic similarities to mainland populations of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="terrestris">B. terrestris</taxonomicName>
lusitanicus
</emphasis>
from the Iberian peninsula (
<bibRefCitation author="WIDMER A &amp; HEMPEL P &amp; ESTOUP A" box="[680,890,947,969]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" pagination="563 - 572" refId="ref10667" refString="WIDMER A., SCHMID- HEMPEL P., ESTOUP A. &amp; A. SCHOLL (1998): Population genetic structure and colonization history of Bombus terrestris s. l. (Hymenoptera: Apidae) from the Canary Islands and Madeira. - Heredity 81: 563 - 572" type="journal article" year="1998">WIDMER et al. 1998</bibRefCitation>
). The variability at microsatellite loci is similar to that of Mediterranean island populations and larger than on the 
<collectingRegion box="[252,410,1005,1027]" country="Spain" name="Canarias" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">Canary Islands</collectingRegion>
. The authors concluded that the occurrence of the mainland and Mediterranean mtDNA haplotype A on 
<collectingRegion box="[587,671,1035,1057]" country="Portugal" name="Madeira" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">Madeira</collectingRegion>
Island is indicative of a different evolutionary history. We classify 
<emphasis box="[479,723,1064,1086]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[479,604,1065,1086]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="terrestris">B. terrestris</taxonomicName>
lusitanicus
</emphasis>
as native and not introduced (see also comments concerning 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="FABRICIUS" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[454,664,1093,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" subSpecies="ruderatus">
<emphasis box="[454,664,1093,1115]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">Bombus r. ruderatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[178,1085,1130,1300]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">
<taxonomicName authority="(FABRICIUS, 1775)" baseAuthorityName="FABRICIUS" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[178,764,1130,1152]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" subGenus="Megabombus" subSpecies="ruderatus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[178,689,1130,1152]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[178,264,1130,1152]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">Bombus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis bold="true" box="[279,420,1130,1152]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">Megabombus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[435,560,1130,1152]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">r. ruderatus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="FABRICIUS J" box="[574,689,1130,1152]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" refId="ref8512" refString="FABRICIUS J. C. (1775): Systema entomologiae sistens insectorum classes, ordines, genera, species, adiectis synonymis, locis, descriptionibus, observationibus. - Flensburgum et Lipsia (Korte). 832 pp." type="book" year="1775">FABRICIUS</bibRefCitation>
</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[702,764,1130,1152]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">1775)</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[765,770,1130,1152]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">:</emphasis>
This species was described by Fabricius in 1775 based on specimens collected by Joseph Banks (first expedition of the Endeavour led by Captain James Cook) on the stop they made in 
<collectingRegion box="[857,941,1189,1211]" country="Portugal" name="Madeira" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">Madeira</collectingRegion>
in 
<date pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" value="1768-09">September 1768</date>
(
<bibRefCitation author="FABRICIUS J" box="[246,419,1219,1241]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" refId="ref8512" refString="FABRICIUS J. C. (1775): Systema entomologiae sistens insectorum classes, ordines, genera, species, adiectis synonymis, locis, descriptionibus, observationibus. - Flensburgum et Lipsia (Korte). 832 pp." type="book" year="1775">FABRICIUS 1775</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="BOIEIRO M &amp; AGUIAR A &amp; REGO C &amp; BORGES P" box="[433,648,1219,1241]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" refId="ref7915" refString="BOIEIRO M., AGUIAR A. F., REGO C., BORGES P. A. V. &amp; A. R. M. SERRANO (2015): The biodiversity of terrestrial arthropods in Madeira and Selvagens archipelagos. - http: // seaentomologia. org / IDE @ / revista _ 6 B. pdf, Revista IDEA; 6 B: 1 - 20." type="book" year="2015">BOIEIRO et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
). The locus typicus of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="FABRICIUS" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[899,1057,1219,1240]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" subSpecies="ruderatus">
<emphasis box="[899,1057,1219,1240]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">B. r. ruderatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is therefore 
<collectingRegion box="[285,370,1248,1270]" country="Portugal" name="Madeira" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">Madeira</collectingRegion>
Island. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="FABRICIUS" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[469,697,1248,1270]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" subSpecies="ruderatus">
<emphasis box="[469,697,1248,1270]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">Bombus r. ruderatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also distributed on the Iberian Peninsula. The central European subspecies is 
<taxonomicName authority="(DALLA TORRE, 1882)" baseAuthorityName="DALLA TORRE" baseAuthorityYear="1882" box="[651,1038,1278,1300]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" subSpecies="eurynotus">
<emphasis box="[651,802,1278,1299]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">B. r. eurynotus</emphasis>
(DALLA TORRE, 1882)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[178,1085,1315,1425]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">
According to 
<bibRefCitation author="RASMONT P" box="[319,497,1315,1337]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" pagination="1 - 72" refId="ref9836" refString="RASMONT P. (1983): Catalogue commente des bourdons de la region ouest-palearctique (Hymenoptera, Apoidea, Apidae). - Not. Faunist. Gembloux 7: 1 - 72." type="journal article" year="1983">RASMONT (1983)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="FABRICIUS" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[508,659,1315,1336]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" subSpecies="ruderatus">
<emphasis box="[508,659,1315,1336]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">B. r. ruderatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed on the 
<collectingRegion box="[877,949,1315,1336]" country="Portugal" name="Acores" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">Azores</collectingRegion>
too (see also 
<bibRefCitation author="YARROW I" box="[178,336,1344,1366]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" pagination="24 - 32" refId="ref10845" refString="YARROW I. H. H. (1967): On the Formicidae of the Azores. - Boletim do M useu municipal do Funchal 21: 24 - 32." type="journal article" year="1967">YARROW 1967</bibRefCitation>
), and was introduced in the 
<collectingRegion box="[652,724,1344,1365]" country="Portugal" name="Acores" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">Azores</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="WEISSMANN J &amp; PICANCO A &amp; BORGES P" box="[742,1001,1344,1366]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" pagination="63 - 95" refId="ref10592" refString="WEISSMANN J. A., PICANCO A., BORGES P. A. V. &amp; H. SCHAEFER (2017): Bees of the Azores: an annotated checklist (Apidae, Hymenoptera). - ZooKeys 642: 63 - 95." type="journal article" year="2017">WEISSMANN et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
), firstly recorded in 1865 (
<bibRefCitation author="GODMAN F" box="[379,540,1374,1396]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" refId="ref8706" refString="GODMAN F. DU CANE (1870): Natural History of the Azores, or Western Islands. J. Van Voorst, London. 377 pp." type="book" year="1870">GODMAN 1870</bibRefCitation>
). On Tenerife, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[709,840,1373,1395]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ruderatus">
<emphasis box="[709,840,1373,1395]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">B. ruderatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is actually an invader (PÉREZ &amp; MACÍAS- HERNÁNDEZ 2012).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="1224" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[178,1085,1440,1609]" lastBlockId="11.[178,1084,219,299]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="1224" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">
Already in the fourteenth century, ships regularly docked on 
<collectingRegion box="[835,919,1440,1462]" country="Portugal" name="Madeira" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">Madeira</collectingRegion>
Island on their return from the 
<collectingRegion box="[346,438,1469,1491]" country="Spain" name="Canarias" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">Canaries</collectingRegion>
. In our opinion we cannot exclude a man-made unintentional introduction. If we compare the distribution with that of 
<emphasis box="[763,924,1499,1520]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">B. t. lusitanicus</emphasis>
on 
<collectingRegion box="[964,1051,1499,1521]" country="Portugal" name="Madeira" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">Madeira</collectingRegion>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1775" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ruderatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">B. ruderatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is restricted to lower altitudes, and the preferred habitats are rural sites, and the preferring flowering ressources are rural plant species. This is not the case for 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">B. t. lusitanicus</emphasis>
, which is also common on 
<collectingRegion box="[573,628,1587,1608]" country="Portugal" name="Porto" pageId="10" pageNumber="1223">Porto</collectingRegion>
Santo, has a habitat preference for the trade wind zone, and is characterised by visiting the flowers of many native plant species (especially 
<emphasis box="[299,376,248,269]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="1224">Echium</emphasis>
); see KRATOCHWIL &amp; SCHWABE (2018a). We studied the flowervisiting behaviour of 
<emphasis box="[395,553,277,299]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="1224">B. t. lusitanicus</emphasis>
intensively on 
<collectingRegion box="[709,764,278,299]" country="Portugal" name="Porto" pageId="11" pageNumber="1224">Porto</collectingRegion>
Santo.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[178,1085,315,366]" pageId="11" pageNumber="1224">Further investigations (especially population genetic analyses) are necessary to determine the rank of ‘native’ or ‘introduced’.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
